GDE Quick Start Guide v2.5

There are two ways to start using the Game Data Editor to manager your data. You can enter the data in manually or import it from a spreadsheet. First I’ll go over manually editing your data.

1. Enter Your Game Data

Using GDE Editor:

  • First, create a schema by specifying data types with the Schema Editor
  • Second, create your data items with the Item Editor

Import Your Game Data From a Spreadsheet:

Choose an import method (Local Excel Workbook or Google Drive) and follow the prompts. Refer to the Spreadsheet Format before importing.

2. Generate Your Data Classes

To generate the GDE Data Classes use the Generate GDE Data Classes menu action. Note: If you are using Playmaker or iCode, skip this step.

3. Include the GameDataEditor namespace

Include the GameDataEditor namespace at the top of any scripts where you will access GDE.

using GameDataEdtor;

4. Initialize GDE

There are 3 ways to initialize GDE. From bundled Resources, from a string, or from a TextAsset.

To initialize with Playmaker, see the Playmaker Quickstart. To initialize with iCode, see the iCode Quickstart.

From Resources:

Include your data file in your game’s Resources by placing the data file in a /Resources path. For example: "Assets/GameDataEditor/Resources/gde_data.txt". Initialize GDE by passing the file name without the file extension:

GDEDataManager.Init("gde_data");

If you encrypted your data with GDE, add “_enc” to the end of your file name and pass “true” for the second parameter.

GDEDataManager.Init("gde_data_enc", true);


From a URL:

To initialize GDE with data from a server, first download the file, and then pass the file contents to GDE.

  1. IEnumerator InitGDE () {
  2.   WWW payload = new WWW("http://example.com/gde_data.txt");
  3.   yield return payload;
  4.  
  5.   if (!GDEDataManager.InitFromText(payload.text)) {
  6.     Debug.LogError("Error initializing!");
  7.   }
  8. }

If your data was encrypted with GDE decrypt your data first:

  1. IEnumerator InitGDE () {
  2.   WWW payload = new WWW("http://example.com/gde_data_enc.bytes");
  3.   yield return payload;
  4.   
  5.   string data = GDEDataManager.DecryptGDEData(payload.bytes);
  6.   if (!GDEDataManager.InitFromText(data)) {
  7.     Debug.LogError("Error initializing!");
  8.   }
  9. }


From a TextAsset:

You can load GDE data from a TextAsset like this:

  1. //Adapted from Unity3D AssetBundle Docs
  2. void Start () {
  3.   var payload = WWW ("http://example.com/myBundle.unity3d");
  4.   yield payload;
  5.  
  6.   TextAsset gde_data = (TextAsset)payload.assetBundle.Load("gde_data", typeof(TextAsset));
  7.  
  8.   if (!GDEDataManager.Init(gde_data)) {
  9.     Debug.LogError("Error initializing!");
  10.   }
  11. }

If you encrypted your data with GDE, call the Init method like this:

GDEDataManager.Init(gde_data, true);

5. Read your data

The generated GDE Data Classes provide properties and methods for reading and saving your items.

To read data with Playmaker, see the Playmaker Quickstart. To read data with iCode, see the iCode Quickstart.

If your Item was defined like this:

Read it like this:

  1. // Make sure GDE is initialized BEFORE reading any item data
  2. void LoadTunic() {
  3.   GDEArmorData tunic;
  4.  
  5.   if (!GDEDataManager.DataDictionary.TryGetCustom(GDEItemKeys.Armor_LeatherTunic, out tunic))
  6.     Debug.LogError("Error reading tunic data!");
  7.  
  8.   //Do something with tunic data
  9.   int totalHP = tunic.hit_points_delta + 100;
  10. }

6. Modify and Save your data

To modify your data during runtime, use the GDE Data Classes you generated.

To modify data with Playmaker, see the Playmaker Quickstart. To modify data with iCode, see the iCode Quickstart.

I’ll use this Warrior item to demonstrate how to modify its data.

Modifying basic types:
Basic types are saved automatically. (Unity types are read only)

  1. void ModifyIDList() {
  2.     GDECharacterData warrior;
  3.     
  4.   if (!GDEDataManager.DataDictionary.TryGetCustom(GDEItemKeys.Character_Warrior, out warrior))
  5.     Debug.LogError("Error reading character data!");
  6.  
  7.   // Any changes to basic field types are saved automatically
  8.   warrior.hp += 100;
  9.   warrior.name = "Celestipoo";
  10. }


Modifying list types:
List types are saved by calling the Set method. (Unity type lists are read only)

  1. void ModifyTunic() {
  2.   GDECharacterData warrior;
  3.  
  4.   if (!GDEDataManager.DataDictionary.TryGetCustom(GDEItemKeys.Character_Warrior, out warrior))
  5.     Debug.LogError("Error reading character data!");
  6.  
  7.   // Modify the list any way you like. 
  8.   // Add, Remove, or Change entries
  9.   // Then call the generated Set method
  10.   warrior.inventory_ids[0] = 314;
  11.   warrior.inventory_ids.Add(1124);
  12.   warrior.inventory_ids.RemoveAt(4);
  13.  
  14.   // Make sure to call Set!!
  15.   warrior.Set_inventory_ids();
  16. }


The modified warrior item from above will always load the modified values until it is reset. You can reset all fields on an item or reset specific fields.

  1. void ResetWarrior() {
  2.   GDECharacterData warrior;
  3.   
  4.   if (!GDEDataManager.DataDictionary.TryGetCustom(GDEItemKeys.Character_Warrior, out warrior))
  5.     Debug.LogError("Error reading warrior data!");
  6.     
  7.   // Reset the inventory_ids field
  8.   warrior.Reset_inventory_ids();
  9.   
  10.   // Reset all fields
  11.   warrior.ResetAll();
  12. }

7. Encrypting Your Data (Optional)

I recommend encrypting your data at, or near, the end of your development cycle. You will need to encrypt your data after any changes from the GDE Editors or when importing from a spreadsheet. To encrypt your data, go to the Encrypt Data menu action:
After encryption is complete, you will see a confirmation dialog. You can click the paths in the dialog to find those files in your project. To load your encrypted data see GDE Init Section.

8. Exporting Data (Optional)

You can export your data to a spreadsheet for editing or archiving. Select the Export Spreadsheet menu, Choose an export method (Local Excel Workbook or Google Drive), and follow the prompts.

9. GDE Preferences

GDE Preferences can be found in Unity Preferences pane.

10. That’s it!

If you have questions you can post a message on the forum or send me an email.

Here is a shortened version of my GDE test class to show you what it looks like all put together.

  1. using UnityEngine;
  2. using System.Collections;
  3. using System.Collections.Generic;
  4.  
  5. using GameDataEditor;
  6.  
  7. public class TwoDListTest : MonoBehaviour {
  8.   GDEMainData data;
  9.  
  10.   // Use this for initialization
  11.   void Start () {
  12.     if (!GDEDataManager.Init("test2d"))
  13.       Debug.LogError("Error initializing!");
  14.     else
  15.     {
  16.       if(!GDEDataManager.DataDictionary.TryGetCustom(GDEItemKeys.Main_DevItem, out data))
  17.         Debug.LogError("Something went wrong :(");
  18.  
  19.       // Now my data is loaded and ready to be used
  20.       // In my test scene, I use it in OnGUI() below
  21.     }
  22.   }
  23.  
  24.   void OnGUI() {
  25.     float x = 0f;
  26.     float y = 0f;
  27.     float lineHeight = 20f;
  28.     Vector2 size;
  29.  
  30.     GUIContent content = new GUIContent("2D List Test");
  31.     size = GUI.skin.label.CalcSize(content);
  32.     GUI.Label(new Rect(x, y, size.x, lineHeight), content);
  33.     y += lineHeight;
  34.  
  35.     content.text = "Bool: ";
  36.     data.b.ForEach(
  37.            l => l.ForEach(
  38.                      itr => {content.text += itr+" | ";}
  39.     ));
  40.  
  41.     size = GUI.skin.label.CalcSize(content);
  42.     GUI.Label(new Rect(x, y, size.x, lineHeight), content);
  43.     y += lineHeight;
  44.  
  45.     // It goes on and on...
  46.   }
  47. }
